  <h1>ğŸ IPL Match Winner Prediction Using Machine Learning (IPL 2026)</h1>

  <p>
    This project is an <strong>AI and Machine Learning based system</strong> designed to
    predict IPL match outcomes using historical match data, feature engineering,
    and machine learning models such as <strong>Random Forest</strong> and
    <strong>XGBoost</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The system also calculates the <strong>correct team win percentage</strong> and
    predicts the <strong>most probable winner of IPL 2026</strong> based on past
    performance.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ“Œ Project Objectives</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Clean and preprocess IPL match dataset</li>
    <li>Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)</li>
    <li>Apply feature engineering for better prediction</li>
    <li>Train and evaluate machine learning models</li>
    <li>Calculate corrected team win percentage</li>
    <li>Predict IPL 2026 winner team</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ“‚ Dataset Description</h2>
  <p>
    The dataset contains IPL match and ball-by-ball level data with columns such as:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>batting_team, bowling_team</li>
    <li>team_runs, team_wicket, overs</li>
    <li>venue, toss_winner, toss_decision</li>
    <li>season, innings</li>
    <li>match_won_by (target column)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    High-cardinality and unnecessary columns such as umpire names, player names,
    IDs, and event metadata were removed during cleaning.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ§¹ Data Cleaning</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Removed irrelevant columns (IDs, umpires, player names)</li>
    <li>Dropped rows with missing match winners</li>
    <li>Handled missing values using forward fill</li>
    <li>Ensured consistent team encoding</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ§  Feature Engineering</h2>
  <p>The following new features were created:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>overs_faced</strong> = team_balls / balls_per_over</li>
    <li><strong>current_run_rate</strong> = team_runs / overs_faced</li>
    <li><strong>wickets_in_hand</strong> = 10 âˆ’ team_wicket</li>
    <li><strong>is_chasing</strong> = 1 if innings = 2, else 0</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ“Š Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Most wins by team</li>
    <li>Impact of toss decision on results</li>
    <li>Venue-wise match distribution</li>
    <li>Season-wise match trend</li>
    <li>Corrected team win percentage analysis</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Graphs and visualizations were created using
    <strong>Matplotlib</strong> and <strong>Seaborn</strong>.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ¤– Machine Learning Models Used</h2>

  <h3>1. Random Forest Classifier</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Used as the primary baseline model</li>
    <li>Handles multi-class classification efficiently</li>
    <li>Provides feature importance</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. XGBoost Classifier</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Gradient boosting based model</li>
    <li>High performance on structured data</li>
    <li>Supports multi-class prediction</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ“ˆ Team Win Percentage Calculation</h2>
  <p>
    Team win percentage is calculated using the corrected formula:
  </p>
  <pre>
Win Percentage = (Total Wins) / (Matches Played as Batting + Bowling) Ã— 100
  </pre>

  <p>
    This avoids incorrect inflation of win percentages and ensures
    fair team comparison.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>ğŸ† IPL 2026 Winner Prediction</h2>
  <p>
    The IPL 2026 winner is predicted based on:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Historical team win percentage</li>
    <li>Overall team performance consistency</li>
    <li>Machine learning insights</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The team with the highest win percentage is selected as the
    <strong>most probable IPL 2026 winner</strong>.
  </p>

